    "id": "vulnerability-scan-network",
    "title": "Vulnerability Scan & Network Security Assessment",
    "description": "Performed in-depth vulnerability scanning and security assessment on a network to identify open ports, misconfigurations, outdated services, and potential security risks. Applied CVSS scoring to evaluate severity and provided actionable remediation steps.",
    "image": "data/images/vulnerability scan.png",
    "tags": ["Nmap", "Wireshark", "Kali Linux", "Network Security", "Vulnerability Assessment"],
    "demoLink": null,
    "githubLink": "https://github.com/Imtiyaz-Ibrahim-NOC",
    "featured": true,
    "content": "<h2>Project Overview</h2><p>This project focuses on performing a complete vulnerability assessment of a network environment. The goal is to identify security weaknesses, analyze risks, and recommend mitigation strategies to improve overall network security posture.</p><h2>Objectives</h2><ul><li>Identify open ports and exposed services</li><li>Detect outdated or vulnerable software versions</li><li>Analyze network traffic for suspicious activity</li><li>Assess risk using CVSS scoring</li><li>Provide remediation and security recommendations</li></ul><h2>Tools & Technologies Used</h2><ul><li><strong>Nmap:</strong> Used for network scanning, port scanning, and service detection</li><li><strong>Wireshark:</strong> Used for packet analysis and monitoring network traffic</li><li><strong>Kali Linux:</strong> Platform used for performing security testing</li><li><strong>Netstat:</strong> Used to view active connections and listening ports</li></ul><h2>Methodology</h2><ol><li><strong>Network Discovery:</strong> Identified active hosts using ping sweep and Nmap scan</li><li><strong>Port Scanning:</strong> Scanned for open ports (e.g., 22, 80, 443)</li><li><strong>Service Enumeration:</strong> Detected running services and versions</li><li><strong>Vulnerability Identification:</strong> Checked for outdated services and known vulnerabilities</li><li><strong>Traffic Analysis:</strong> Used Wireshark to monitor suspicious packets</li><li><strong>Risk Assessment:</strong> Assigned severity using CVSS scoring</li><li><strong>Reporting:</strong> Documented findings and suggested fixes</li></ol><h2>Key Findings</h2><ul><li>Open ports exposed unnecessarily (e.g., Telnet, FTP)</li><li>Outdated software versions with known vulnerabilities</li><li>Weak or default configurations</li><li>Unencrypted traffic detected</li></ul><h2>Example</h2><p>During scanning, port 23 (Telnet) was found open on a server. Telnet is insecure because it transmits data in plain text. This can allow attackers to capture sensitive information using packet sniffing tools.</p><h2>CVSS Scoring Example</h2><ul><li><strong>Vulnerability:</strong> Open Telnet Port</li><li><strong>Severity:</strong> High</li><li><strong>Score:</strong> 8.2</li></ul><h2>Recommendations</h2><ul><li>Disable unused ports and services</li><li>Replace insecure protocols (Telnet → SSH)</li><li>Regularly update and patch systems</li><li>Implement firewall rules and access control</li><li>Use encryption for sensitive data transmission</li></ul><h2>Outcome</h2><p>This project helped improve network security by identifying critical vulnerabilities and applying best practices. It also provided hands-on experience with real-world cybersecurity tools and techniques used in NOC and SOC environments.</p>"
